org.chronos.chronodb.internal.api

Interface TemporalDataMatrix

  • All Known Implementing Classes:
    AbstractTemporalDataMatrix, TemporalChunkDbDataMatrix, TemporalInMemoryMatrix, TemporalJdbcMatrix, TemporalMapDBMatrix, TemporalTuplMatrix

    public interface TemporalDataMatrix
    A TemporalDataMatrix is a structured container for temporal key-value pairs.

    Such a matrix is defined over a set of timestamps T, in combination with a set of keys K. A temporal data matrix D is then defined as D = T x K. The matrix can be visualized as follows: 

        K

    ^
    |
    |
    +----+----+----+----+----+
  c |    | V2 |    |    |    |
    +----+----+----+----+----+
  b |    |    | V4 |    |  X |
    +----+----+----+----+----+
  a | V1 |    | V3 |    |    |
    +----+----+----+----+----+---> T
       1    2    3    4    5
    In the example above, the following inserts have been applied:
    • a->V1 at T = 1
    • c->v2 at T = 2
    • a->v3, b-> v4 at T = 3
    • b->deleted at T = 5
    Each entry in such a matrix D has a certain validity range on the T axis. For example, the entry "a->V1" is valid in range [1;3[, while "b->V4" is valid in [3;5[. In general, each entry is valid from (including) the timestamp at which it was inserted, up to the timestamp where the next insert occurs (exclusive).

      • get

        GetResult<byte[]> get(long timestamp,
                      java.lang.String key)
        Returns the value for the given key at the given timestamp together with the time range in which it is valid.
        Parameters:
        timestamp - The timestamp at which to get the value for the given key. Must not be negative.
        key - The key to get the value for. Must not be null.
        Returns:
        A ranged result. The result object itself is guaranteed to be non-null. Contains the value for the given key at the given timestamp, or contains a null-value if the key does not exist in this matrix at the given timestamp. The range of the returned object represents the period in which the given key is bound to the returned value.

      • history

        java.util.Iterator<java.lang.Long> history(long maxTime,
                                           java.lang.String key)
        Returns the history of the given key, i.e. all timestamps at which the given key changed its value due to a commit.
        Parameters:
        maxTime - The maximum timestamp to consider. Only timestamps equal to or lower than this value will be considered. Must not be negative.
        key - The key to get the commit timestamps for. Must not be null.
        Returns:
        An iterator over all commit timestamps on the given key, up to the given maximum timestamp. May be empty, but never null.

      • allEntriesIterator

        CloseableIterator<UnqualifiedTemporalEntry> allEntriesIterator(long timestamp)
        Returns an iterator over all entries in this matrix.
        Parameters:
        timestamp - The timestamp at which the iteration takes place. Only entries with timestamps up to this timestamp will be considered. Must not be negative.
        Returns:
        An iterator over all entries up to the given timestamp. May be empty, but never null.

      • lastCommitTimestamp

        long lastCommitTimestamp(java.lang.String key)
        Returns the timestamp at which the last (latest) commit has happened on the given key.
        Parameters:
        key - The key in question. Must not be null.
        Returns:
        The latest commit timestamp, or a negative value if there has never been a commit to this key in this matrix.

      • put

        void put(long timestamp,
         java.util.Map<java.lang.String,byte[]> contents)
        Adds the given contents to this matrix, at the given timestamp.
        Parameters:
        timestamp - The timestamp at which to add the given contents to this matrix. Must not be negative.

      • insertEntries

      • rollback

        void rollback(long timestamp)
        Performs a rollback of the contents of this matrix to the given timestamp.

        Any entries which have been inserted after the given timestamp will be removed during the process.

        Parameters:
        timestamp - The timestamp to roll back to. Must not be negative.

      • keySetModifications

        Parameters:

        Returns:
        the keyset modifications. May be empty, but never null.
